1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,259
For a transformer to understand a sentence,

2
00:00:03,259 --> 00:00:07,451
it must know not just what the words are,

3
00:00:07,451 --> 00:00:09,314
but where they are.

4
00:00:09,314 --> 00:00:13,505
In the original Attention Is All You Need paper,

5
00:00:13,505 --> 00:00:17,697
researchers added absolute positional embeddings directly to token vectors.

6
00:00:17,697 --> 00:00:20,957
Think of this as assigning every word

7
00:00:20,957 --> 00:00:23,751
a fixed coordinate on a map.

8
00:00:23,751 --> 00:00:26,545
But language is relative, not absolute.

9
00:00:26,545 --> 00:00:30,271
If you shift a sentence by three tokens,

10
00:00:30,271 --> 00:00:34,928
its meaning stays the same, yet absolute coordinates change completely.

11
00:00:34,928 --> 00:00:37,722
While relative positional embeddings solve this,

12
00:00:37,722 --> 00:00:42,379
they require complex attention bias matrices that degrade hardware performance.

13
00:00:42,379 --> 00:00:46,105
To break this impasse, modern architectures like Llama,

14
00:00:46,105 --> 00:00:50,297
Mistral, and Gemma use Rotary Position Embeddings, or RoPE.

15
00:00:50,297 --> 00:00:53,557
RoPE represents positions geometrically, combining the absolute

16
00:00:53,557 --> 00:00:58,679
efficiency of additive embeddings with the mathematical elegance of relative distance.

17
00:00:58,679 --> 00:01:03,276
To understand RoPE, we must step into the complex plane.

18
00:01:03,276 --> 00:01:06,493
Imagine a two-dimensional vector representing our token.

19
00:01:06,493 --> 00:01:11,089
In absolute embeddings, we push this vector in some direction.

20
00:01:11,089 --> 00:01:13,387
In RoPE, we rotate it.

21
00:01:13,387 --> 00:01:17,524
By multiplying our vector by a two-dimensional rotation matrix,

22
00:01:17,524 --> 00:01:22,120
we rotate it by an angle proportional to its position,

23
00:01:22,120 --> 00:01:24,877
m, times a base frequency, theta.

24
00:01:24,877 --> 00:01:28,095
This rotation alters the vector's phase while

25
00:01:28,095 --> 00:01:30,393
leaving its magnitude completely unchanged.

26
00:01:30,393 --> 00:01:33,150
Because rotation is a linear operator,

27
00:01:33,150 --> 00:01:36,368
it preserves the geometric relationships between vectors.

28
00:01:36,368 --> 00:01:40,504
If we rotate two vectors by the same angle,

29
00:01:40,504 --> 00:01:44,181
their relative distance and inner product remain identical.

30
00:01:44,181 --> 00:01:47,398
This simple rotation in two dimensions is

31
00:01:47,398 --> 00:01:50,615
the fundamental building block of sequence geometry.

32
00:01:50,615 --> 00:01:53,939
But transformer hidden dimensions are not two-dimensional;

33
00:01:53,939 --> 00:01:56,787
they are typically thousands of dimensions.

34
00:01:56,787 --> 00:01:58,686
How does RoPE scale?

35
00:01:58,686 --> 00:02:02,010
It does so by partitioning the high-dimensional

36
00:02:02,010 --> 00:02:06,283
vector space into a series of independent two-dimensional planes.

37
00:02:06,283 --> 00:02:09,131
For a vector of dimension d,

38
00:02:09,131 --> 00:02:12,455
RoPE groups adjacent coordinates into d-over-two pairs.

39
00:02:12,455 --> 00:02:15,778
Each pair is rotated in its own

40
00:02:15,778 --> 00:02:18,627
two-dimensional plane with a unique frequency,

41
00:02:18,627 --> 00:02:23,849
theta-sub-i, which decreases exponentially as we go deeper into the dimensions.

42
00:02:23,849 --> 00:02:28,122
We represent this as a sparse, block-diagonal rotation matrix.

43
00:02:28,122 --> 00:02:32,869
In practice, we don't even perform a full matrix multiplication.

44
00:02:32,869 --> 00:02:36,193
We implement RoPE as a highly efficient,

45
00:02:36,193 --> 00:02:39,516
element-wise vector operation, applying sine and cosine

46
00:02:39,516 --> 00:02:42,839
transformations directly to coordinate pairs in parallel.

47
00:02:42,840 --> 00:02:47,745
The true magic of RoPE lies in the self-attention dot product.

48
00:02:47,745 --> 00:02:50,867
When a Query at position m attends

49
00:02:50,867 --> 00:02:53,543
to a Key at position n,

50
00:02:53,543 --> 00:02:57,557
both vectors have been rotated by their respective positions.

51
00:02:57,557 --> 00:03:00,679
Mathematically, the dot product of the rotated

52
00:03:00,679 --> 00:03:03,801
Query and Key is equivalent to multiplying

53
00:03:03,801 --> 00:03:06,923
the Query transpose by the transpose of

54
00:03:06,923 --> 00:03:09,153
the rotation matrix of m,

55
00:03:09,153 --> 00:03:13,612
times the rotation matrix of n, times the Key vector.

56
00:03:13,612 --> 00:03:16,288
Because these rotation matrices are orthogonal,

57
00:03:16,288 --> 00:03:19,410
their product simplifies to a single rotation

58
00:03:19,410 --> 00:03:22,978
matrix of the relative distance, n minus m.

59
00:03:22,978 --> 00:03:26,100
Thus, the attention score depends solely on

60
00:03:26,100 --> 00:03:28,776
the relative distance between the tokens,

61
00:03:28,776 --> 00:03:33,236
even though we only applied absolute transformations to individual vectors.

62
00:03:33,236 --> 00:03:35,466
Furthermore, as relative distance increases,

63
00:03:35,466 --> 00:03:39,479
the dot product naturally decays, matching human linguistic intuition.

64
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:43,917
By marrying absolute encoding efficiency with relative attention mechanics,

65
00:03:43,917 --> 00:03:48,848
RoPE has become the undisputed standard for modern language models.

66
00:03:48,848 --> 00:03:53,779
Its geometric foundation offers another massive advantage: context length extrapolation.

67
00:03:53,779 --> 00:03:57,231
Because positions are represented as continuous rotations,

68
00:03:57,231 --> 00:04:00,682
we can extend the model's context window

69
00:04:00,682 --> 00:04:04,134
after training by interpolating the rotation angles—a

70
00:04:04,134 --> 00:04:08,079
technique known as RoPE Scaling or NTK-aware scaling.

71
00:04:08,079 --> 00:04:11,530
This allows models trained on four thousand

72
00:04:11,530 --> 00:04:16,954
tokens to effortlessly handle tens of thousands without retraining from scratch.

73
00:04:16,954 --> 00:04:20,406
If you want to keep exploring the

74
00:04:20,406 --> 00:04:23,858
physical and mathematical architectures shaping artificial intelligence,

75
00:04:23,858 --> 00:04:29,282
hit the subscribe button for Gemini three point five Flash Model.

76
00:04:29,282 --> 00:04:33,719
Let's keep rotating the boundaries of speed and scale.
